Step 1: Check whether provider table has numeric provider_id values

Run this first:

SELECT
    COUNT(*) AS TOTAL_ROWS,
    COUNT(TRY_TO_NUMBER(PROVIDER_ID)) AS NUMERIC_PROVIDER_ID_ROWS
FROM FWRB_PRD_WMIDR_DB.CASENET.PROVIDER;
What this tells you
If NUMERIC_PROVIDER_ID_ROWS is very low or 0, then this join will fail:
TRY_TO_NUMBER(p.PROVIDER_ID) = s.PROVIDER_ID
Step 2: See sample provider_id values from provider table
SELECT DISTINCT
    PROVIDER_ID
FROM FWRB_PRD_WMIDR_DB.CASENET.PROVIDER
LIMIT 50;

Check whether values look like:

12345 → numeric, join may work
P12345 or ABC001 → numeric cast will fail
GUID-like values → wrong join key
Step 3: Check specialty table by itself

Make sure it has data:

SELECT
    COUNT(*) AS TOTAL_ROWS,
    COUNT(DISTINCT PROVIDER_ID) AS DISTINCT_PROVIDER_IDS,
    COUNT(DISTINCT PROVIDER_SPECIALTY_CODE) AS DISTINCT_SPECIALTY_CODES
FROM FWRB_PRD_WMIDR_DB.BI_ANALYSIS.DIM_PROVIDER_SPECIALTY;

Then:

SELECT
    ACTIVE_FLAG,
    COUNT(*) AS CNT
FROM FWRB_PRD_WMIDR_DB.BI_ANALYSIS.DIM_PROVIDER_SPECIALTY
GROUP BY ACTIVE_FLAG
ORDER BY ACTIVE_FLAG;

If ACTIVE_FLAG = 1 has no rows, that explains everything.

Step 4: Test provider-to-specialty join only

Remove the lookup table first.

SELECT
    COUNT(*) AS JOINED_ROWS
FROM FWRB_PRD_WMIDR_DB.CASENET.PROVIDER p
JOIN FWRB_PRD_WMIDR_DB.BI_ANALYSIS.DIM_PROVIDER_SPECIALTY s
    ON TRY_TO_NUMBER(p.PROVIDER_ID) = s.PROVIDER_ID;
Result meaning
If this returns 0, the problem is between PROVIDER and DIM_PROVIDER_SPECIALTY
If this returns rows, then the problem is the lookup table join
Step 5: Test lookup table separately

Check whether lookup table has data:

SELECT
    COUNT(*) AS TOTAL_ROWS,
    COUNT(DISTINCT PROVIDER_SPECIALTY_CODE) AS DISTINCT_CODES
FROM FWRB_PRD_WMIDR_DB.BI_ANALYSIS.DIM_PROVIDER_SPECIALTY_LKP;

Then:

SELECT
    ACTIVE_FLAG,
    COUNT(*) AS CNT
FROM FWRB_PRD_WMIDR_DB.BI_ANALYSIS.DIM_PROVIDER_SPECIALTY_LKP
GROUP BY ACTIVE_FLAG
ORDER BY ACTIVE_FLAG;

Then test specialty-to-lookup join:

SELECT
    COUNT(*) AS JOINED_ROWS
FROM FWRB_PRD_WMIDR_DB.BI_ANALYSIS.DIM_PROVIDER_SPECIALTY s
JOIN FWRB_PRD_WMIDR_DB.BI_ANALYSIS.DIM_PROVIDER_SPECIALTY_LKP l
    ON s.PROVIDER_SPECIALTY_CODE = l.PROVIDER_SPECIALTY_CODE;

If this gives rows, lookup is fine.

Step 6: Use LEFT JOIN to see where it breaks

This is the best diagnostic query:

SELECT
    p.PROVIDER_ID AS P_PROVIDER_ID,
    TRY_TO_NUMBER(p.PROVIDER_ID) AS P_PROVIDER_ID_NUM,
    s.PROVIDER_ID AS S_PROVIDER_ID,
    s.PROVIDER_SPECIALTY_CODE,
    l.PROVIDER_SPECIALTY_DESC,
    l.PROVIDER_SPECIALTY_TYPE
FROM FWRB_PRD_WMIDR_DB.CASENET.PROVIDER p
LEFT JOIN FWRB_PRD_WMIDR_DB.BI_ANALYSIS.DIM_PROVIDER_SPECIALTY s
    ON TRY_TO_NUMBER(p.PROVIDER_ID) = s.PROVIDER_ID
LEFT JOIN FWRB_PRD_WMIDR_DB.BI_ANALYSIS.DIM_PROVIDER_SPECIALTY_LKP l
    ON s.PROVIDER_SPECIALTY_CODE = l.PROVIDER_SPECIALTY_CODE
LIMIT 100;
Why this helps

You will see:

whether TRY_TO_NUMBER(p.PROVIDER_ID) is null
whether specialty join is failing
whether lookup join is failing
Most likely issue

I strongly suspect this:

CASENET.PROVIDER.PROVIDER_ID is not the same key as BI_ANALYSIS.DIM_PROVIDER_SPECIALTY.PROVIDER_ID

Even though both columns are called PROVIDER_ID, they may come from different systems.

This happens a lot.

For example:

CASENET.PROVIDER.PROVIDER_ID could be a source-system provider key
BI_ANALYSIS.DIM_PROVIDER_SPECIALTY.PROVIDER_ID could be a warehouse surrogate key

If that is true, they will never join directly.

Step 7: Compare sample values from both tables

Run these side by side.

Provider table
SELECT DISTINCT
    PROVIDER_ID
FROM FWRB_PRD_WMIDR_DB.CASENET.PROVIDER
LIMIT 20;
Specialty table
SELECT DISTINCT
    PROVIDER_ID
FROM FWRB_PRD_WMIDR_DB.BI_ANALYSIS.DIM_PROVIDER_SPECIALTY
LIMIT 20;

If the values look completely different, that confirms the join key is wrong.

Step 8: Check if NPI may be the real link

Your provider table has NPI.

If your claim/provider specialty side has another table that maps provider_id to NPI, that may be the real bridge.

Try checking whether DIM_PROVIDER_SPECIALTY has a path through some DIM_PROVIDER, DIM_RENDERING_PROVIDER, or DIM_BILLING_PROVIDER table.

Search your BI schema for tables like:

DIM_PROVIDER
DIM_CLAIM_PROVIDER
BRIDGE_PROVIDER
PROVIDER_XREF

Because often:

claims use warehouse provider id
casenet provider uses source provider id
NPI is the common business key
Quick isolation queries

These will tell you exactly where the problem is.

A. Does provider-specialty join work?
SELECT COUNT(*)
FROM FWRB_PRD_WMIDR_DB.CASENET.PROVIDER p
JOIN FWRB_PRD_WMIDR_DB.BI_ANALYSIS.DIM_PROVIDER_SPECIALTY s
  ON TRY_TO_NUMBER(p.PROVIDER_ID) = s.PROVIDER_ID;
B. Does specialty-lookup join work?
SELECT COUNT(*)
FROM FWRB_PRD_WMIDR_DB.BI_ANALYSIS.DIM_PROVIDER_SPECIALTY s
JOIN FWRB_PRD_WMIDR_DB.BI_ANALYSIS.DIM_PROVIDER_SPECIALTY_LKP l
  ON s.PROVIDER_SPECIALTY_CODE = l.PROVIDER_SPECIALTY_CODE;
C. Does active filter remove everything?
SELECT COUNT(*)
FROM FWRB_PRD_WMIDR_DB.BI_ANALYSIS.DIM_PROVIDER_SPECIALTY s
WHERE s.ACTIVE_FLAG = 1;
SELECT COUNT(*)
FROM FWRB_PRD_WMIDR_DB.BI_ANALYSIS.DIM_PROVIDER_SPECIALTY_LKP l
WHERE l.ACTIVE_FLAG = 1;
